= Importizer
:toc:

Are you looking to convert your header-based C{plus}{plus} codebase to C{plus}{plus}20 modules, but afraid that modularizing is too cumbersome? *importizer* is here to help.

And by modularization I don’t mean exposing a module interface and wrapping. headers. I mean native modules a.k.a using modules internally.

*Note:* This project is currently going through a complete rewrite using Clang LibTooling to replace Regex (pre-2.0.0). Much pre-2.0.0 things are gone, but releases and git history are still preserved.

This project uses https://semver.org[semantic versioning].

== Why Native C{plus}{plus} Modules?

* *Improved compilation time:* Modules don’t need to be recompiled every time it is imported, unlike headers.
* *Improved encapsulation:* Modules allow you to choose what is exposed to users (exported), no need to hide stuff with a `detail` namespace. Includes and macros from a module will only stay in that module.
* https://arewemodulesyet.org

== Prebuilt Binaries

Importizer provides pre-compiled binaries for major operating systems. Because the tool relies on Clang LibTooling, the necessary shared libraries are bundled directly in the distribution archive.

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |macOS |Windows
|Architecture |x64, arm64 |x64, arm64  |x64, arm64^1^
|Minimum OS |glibc 2.35{plus} |macOS 15{plus} |Windows 10{plus}
|Format |tar.gz(bin {plus} .so) |tar.gz(bin {plus} .dylib) |zip(bin {plus} .dll)
|===

. Microsoft can't https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/t/Launch-VsDevShellps1-does-not-allow-arm/10740584[support their own tool]

*Downloads:*

* *Stable Releases (Recommended):* Download optimized release builds from the https://github.com/msqr1/importizer/releases[Releases page].
* *Bleeding Edge (Debug):* Download unoptimized builds with sanitizers enabled from the https://github.com/msqr1/importizer/releases/tag/continuous[continuous tag]. Useful for testing latest features or reporting bugs.

== Configuration & Usage

Importizer is primarily driven by a TOML configuration file, complemented by a few command-line arguments.

=== Command-Line Interface (CLI)

By default, running `importizer` looks for an `importizer.toml` file in the current working directory. You can override this by passing the path as a positional argument: `importizer` `path/to/config.toml`.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Description
|-h, --help |Print help information and exit.
|-v, --version |Print version information and exit.
|-o, --outDir |Override the output directory specified in the config file.
|-r, --raw |Disable ANSI styling in logs (`always` or `never`). Defaults to `always` if no value is provided. Can also be toggled via the `RAW` environment variable.
|===

=== Configuration File (TOML)

All relative paths defined in the configuration file are resolved relative to the configuration file’s location, *not* the current working directory.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Type |Description
|`inDir` |String |*Required.* The directory containing the source code to process.
|`outDir` |String |*Required* (unless provided via CLI). The directory for the modularized output.
|`compilationDb` |String |*Highly Recommended.* Path to a `compile_commands.json` compilation database to provide accurate AST parsing context.
|===

==== Fallback: Bootstrap Mode

For projects without a JSON compilation database, Importizer can attempt to imitate one using the `[bootstrap]` table. Note: If `compilationDb` is specified, the `bootstrap` table is ignored.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Type |Default |Description
|`hdrExts` |String Array |`["h","hh","hpp","hxx",""]` |Header file extensions used in the project.
|`srcExts` |String Array |`["cc","cpp","cxx","c{plus}{plus}","C"]` |Source file extensions used in the project.
|`includePaths` |String Array |`[]` |Include paths to search during AST parsing.
|===

=== Example config file

[source,toml]
----
inDir = "src"
outDir = "modular_src"
# compilationDb = "build/compile_commands.json"

[bootstrap]
includePaths = ["include", "third_party/libs"]
----

== Developing

=== Build Environment

The following tools have been tested and verified for building from source.

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |MacOS |Windows
|Generator |Ninja^1^, Makefile | Ninja^1^| Ninja^1^, Visual Studio
|Compiler |GCC, Clang |Clang |clang-cl^2^
|===

. Highly recommended for faster builds
. I try to support MSVC but it never worked, MSVC is also slower

=== Dependency Linkage

Because Importizer relies heavily on Clang LibTooling and LLVM, the resulting binary linkage varies by operating system

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |MacOS |Windows
|LibTooling |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^
|LLVM |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^
|LibC |Dynamic^4^ |Dynamic^2^ |Dynamic^3^
|LibC{plus}{plus} |Static |Dynamic^2^ |Static
|Other 3rd-party |Static |Static |Static
|===

. Package manager doesn’t offer static version, pending self-built LLVM
. Dynamic with stable ABI guaranteed by macOS (libSystem), we can treat as if static
. Dynamic with stable ABI guaranteed by Windows (UCRT), we can treat as if static
. Dynamic glibc, pending switch to a static libc (musl, LLVM libc)

=== Building from Source

Importizer uses a standard CMake build process. To clone and build the release executable:

[source,bash]
----
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/msqr1/importizer
cd importizer

# Configure the project
cmake -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release

# Build using all available cores
cmake --build build --config Release -j $(cmake -P scripts/Nproc.cmake)
----

* The compiled executable will be located in the `build` directory

=== Running Tests

Tests are not enabled by default, but can be toggled via the `BUILD_TESTING` CMake option.

[source,bash]
----
# Ensure tests are configured (Debug mode recommended for testing)
cmake -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug -DBUILD_TESTING=ON
cmake --build build --config Debug -j $(cmake -P scripts/Nproc.cmake)

# Run the test suite using all available cores
ctest --test-dir build/tests --output-on-failure --progress --schedule-random -j $(cmake -P scripts/Nproc.cmake)
----

=== Adding New Tests

Importizer uses a custom directory-based test harness (located in `src/run-test`). To add a new test case:

. Create a new directory under `tests/` with a descriptive name (e.g., `tests/my-new-feature/`).
. Add a `Config.toml` file inside this directory to configure the importizer run.
. Add a `RefCli.txt` file containing the expected CLI output.
. *(Optional)* Create a `in/` subdirectory containing the input files (C{plus}{plus} header-based code).
. *(Optional)* Create a `ref/` subdirectory containing the expected output files. The test driver will automatically compare the actual output directory against this reference directory. Don’t add this when expecting an error.

The CMake script dynamically globs the `tests/` folder, so your new test will be automatically picked up on the next `cmake` `-B` `build` run.

== Contributing to Importizer

Thank you for helping to improve Importizer! Because this project heavily leverages Clang LibTooling, the C{plus}{plus} conventions closely mirror the LLVM coding standards.

=== Naming Conventions

* *C{plus}{plus} & CMake Variables/Functions:* `camelCase`
* *C{plus}{plus} Classes, Types, & Files:* `PascalCase` (e.g., `MyClass.cc`)
* *Executables & Directories:* `kebab-case` (e.g., `run-test/`)
* *CMake External Variables:* `ALL_CAPS_SNAKE_CASE`

=== C{plus}{plus} Code Style

* Follow the LLVM coding style. We enforce a 90-column line limit, which is automatically handled by our `.clang_format` file.
* Use `std::string_view` over `const` `char*`, and `std::array`/`std::vector` over C-style arrays.
* Use angled brackets (`#include` `<header.h>`) for external/third-party headers.
* The C{plus}{plus} file containing `main()` for any executable must be named `Driver.cc`.
* Maintain the exact same ordering of options in the Options section and parsing logic in `getOpts`.

=== Error Handling (Without Exceptions)

Like LLVM, Importizer *does not use C{plus}{plus} exceptions*.

* *Return Values:* Mark fallible functions with `[nodiscard]` and return `bool` (or a type implicitly convertible to `bool`).
* *Logging:* Functions must handle logging their own errors and should be marked `noexcept`.
* *System Errors:* Mark branches handling system-level errors (e.g., `fseek` or `ftell` failures) with `[unlikely]`. Do not use this for standard user input validation.
* *Early Exits:* For an errorless early exit (e.g., the user requested `--help` or `--version`), return `std::optional<bool>` with `std::nullopt` to signal to the caller that execution should halt successfully without an error code.

=== Build System (CMake)

* Always place `common-config` as the *first* item in your `target_link_libraries` list.
* Only use generator expressions for build-time conditionals, not for configure-time conditionals.
* Check a compiler/linker flag if it's not guaranteed to be available (e.g., `-fsanitize=address`)
* `3rd-party folder` must only contain 3rd-party libraries used by the project
* Use `target_*_*` to add flags for this project, and `add_*_*` to add for this and all dependencies.

=== Checklists

When bumping the version for a new release, update the version string in:

* `.github/workflows/Release.yml`
* `src/importizer/Opts.cc`
* `CMakeLists.txt`

When bumping LibTooling version, update the version string in:
* `.github/actions/EnsureLibtooling.yml`
* `scripts/libtooling/GetLlvm.cmake`
